      See user manual for safety instructions. Always use on healthy muscles, avoid injured or inflamed areas, and do not use on sensitive body parts. Keep the device dry and away from water.       Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

      • The Skeptical Shopper
        4.0 out of 5 stars One of the Best Guns I've Ever Had Pointed At Me.
        Reviewed in the United States on April 7, 2024
        Verified Purchase
        Early Need-to-Know Stuff:
        - Decent attachments but could use about 2 more that seem to be basic in most other kits.
        - Battery life is middle quality. Can fizzle out in the middle of a session if you're not fully charged.
        - Attachments can be a little tough to tug out of the gun when finished.
        - Price is super agreeable for what's included.

        Full Review:
        After 30, sometimes stupid things hurt. Like, if you sleep in the wrong position, or if you hold in a sneeze. So, after about 20 minutes on our kids' new trampoline, I felt like I might die. My muscles were super sore, and whacking them with a ladle wasn't helping. My spouse suggested this massage gun. As always, I was skeptical. Seemed like another thing that would clutter up closets, but it was cheap so I agreed. With Prime's bizarrely fast next-day shipping, it got here before my muscles had recouped, but not before my ladle bent. After following the charging instructions, I hooked up the deep tissue attachment. Skeptical no more! Involuntary sounds came from some part of me locked under the muscle knots. The gun is a little noisy, but not enough to distract me from the feeling of relief. There are higher end units out there. This gun lacks some attachments that others offer that seem beneficial. The battery life on mine doesn't seem to last as long as I would hope. And there is nothing worse then getting halfway through releasing a pinched nerve when the battery poops out. Changing the attachments seemed a little tough sometimes. Putting the attachment into the gun was easy, but sometimes tugging the old attachment out to put the gun away is enough to cause a need to use it again. If you're in your 20's, buy it to keep in your yoga bag or to have after a lovely hike with whoever you're dating. If you're over 30 and don't have one of these, especially if you have kids, I wonder what's taking you so long. My spouse has another massage gun we bought on here. Both are pretty comparable, but the battery life on this one was shorter. Of course, it was half the price, so pretty darn worth it in my opinion.
